<!-- 48-HOUR EXEC SUMMARY -->
<div class="section">48-hour operational summary — 18 Mar 09:00 to 20 Mar 09:00</div>
<div class="card">
  <ul class="exec48">
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Attack waves</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val amber">~130 total</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">Iran: ~30 &nbsp;·&nbsp; Hezbollah: ~100</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>Iran (18–20 Mar):</b> Multiple barrages including 5 salvos at Jerusalem and northern Israel within a single hour on 19 Mar. Energy infrastructure targeting confirmed — Haifa's Bazan refinery hit by Iranian missile fragments 19 Mar; fire extinguished, no casualties, but refinery disclosed additional structural damage on 20 Mar requiring days to restore. Iran missile rate has declined ~90% from day-1 levels per CENTCOM/JINSA, attributed to launcher destruction and stock depletion.<br>
        <b>Hezbollah (18–20 Mar):</b> ~50 waves per 48hrs. 19 Mar: rockets wounded 3 in northern Israel; a projectile directly struck a building in Kiryat Shmona. 20 Mar: woman (70s) transported to hospital with moderate injuries after failing to reach shelter during missile alert.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-down">↓ IRAN DECLINING</span> Iran missile tempo down ~90% from war peak — launcher attrition and stock depletion the primary drivers per US Admiral Brad Cooper. However, remaining missiles are <b>larger (1,000kg+ payloads)</b> — Iran has shifted from saturation to high-impact penetration strikes. Fewer but more destructive.
      </div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Casualties (Israel, 48hrs)</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val red">0 killed &nbsp;·&nbsp; ~10 wounded</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">Period total: 18 civilians killed · 3,750+ wounded</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>19 Mar:</b> No fatalities in Israel. 3 wounded in Kiryat Shmona (Hezbollah rocket, building hit directly). Multiple missile fragments caused property damage across northern Israel. Haifa refinery hit — no casualties. Fragments in Shfaram and Kiryat Ata (no injuries). <b>20 Mar (early):</b> Woman (70s) with moderate injuries while rushing to shelter (Rehovot area). Home in Rehovot damaged by falling missile fragments — missile piece found inside living room (MDA photo). No fatalities confirmed.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-down">↓ LOWER CASUALTY TEMPO</span> No Israeli civilian fatalities in 48hrs — a notable improvement after 3 killed in previous 48hrs. However shelter non-compliance injuries continuing. Refinery hit demonstrates Iran's shift to infrastructure targeting is expanding inside Israel. Total war toll remains: 18 civilians + 2 soldiers killed.
      </div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Peak attack hours</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val green">Distributed</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">No single overnight surge · multiple daytime waves</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>19 Mar:</b> Iran launched 5 salvos at Jerusalem and northern Israel within a single hour during daylight hours — a reversal from the previous 01:00–05:00 pre-dawn pattern. Multiple daytime siren activations across central and northern Israel. <b>20 Mar:</b> Early morning alerts and fragment damage (Rehovot) suggest overnight barrage resumed.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-stable">→ PATTERN SHIFTING</span> Pre-dawn surge (18–19 Mar) appears to have been a temporary tactical spike tied to Larijani revenge. Attack distribution returning to a mixed day/night tempo. However, the shift to daytime concentrated salvos (5 within 1 hour) is new — likely testing air-defence response cycles. Daytime strikes increase risk to civilians outdoors and at workplaces.
      </div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Weapons &amp; targets</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val red">Infrastructure shift</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">Haifa refinery hit · F-35 downed · 1,000kg+ payloads</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>Iran (19–20 Mar):</b> Haifa Bazan refinery hit by Iranian missile fragments — fire extinguished, no casualties, but additional infrastructure damage disclosed 20 Mar. Iran confirmed using missiles with 1,000kg+ payloads as of 10 Mar, shifting from saturation to precision. A US F-35 made emergency landing after apparent Iranian hit (pilot stable). Iran hit Qatar's Ras Laffan LNG (20% world supply), Kuwaiti refineries, Saudi facilities — regional energy war escalating.<br>
        <b>Hezbollah (19 Mar):</b> Rockets + missiles directly struck building in Kiryat Shmona. 3 wounded. Standard rocket/UAV pattern continues — no new weapon types observed.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-new">⚠ KEY SHIFT</span> Iran is now targeting Israeli energy infrastructure inside Israel (Haifa refinery) in retaliation for Israeli strike on South Pars gasfield. Netanyahu confirmed Israel "acted alone" on South Pars. Energy infrastructure attacks on both sides represent a significant escalation beyond the missile/population centre exchange. Trump has asked Israel to hold off on future energy strikes — Israel has agreed for now.
      </div>
    </li>
  </ul>
